hands_on_practices.solution:
Starting from the perfect fluid stress-energy tensor in natural units,
$$T^{\mu
u} = (ho + p) u^{\mu} u^{
u} + p g^{\mu
u},$$
the mixed tensor is obtained by lowering one index with the metric:
$$T^{\mu}{}_{
u} \equiv T^{\mu\alpha} g_{\alpha
u} = (ho + p) u^{\mu} u^{\alpha} g_{\alpha
u} + p g^{\mu\alpha} g_{\alpha
u}.$$
Using $u_{
u} \equiv g_{
u\alpha} u^{\alpha}$ and $g^{\mu\alpha} g_{\alpha
u} = \delta^{\mu}{}_{
u}$, this becomes
$$T^{\mu}{}_{
u} = (ho + p) u^{\mu} u_{
u} + p \delta^{\mu}{}_{
u}.$$

To find eigenvalues and eigenvectors, act on the four-velocity $u^{
u}$:
$$T^{\mu}{}_{
u} u^{
u} = (ho + p) u^{\mu} u_{
u} u^{
u} + p \delta^{\mu}{}_{
u} u^{
u}.$$
Using the normalization $u^{
u} u_{
u} = -1$, we obtain
$$T^{\mu}{}_{
u} u^{
u} = -(ho + p) u^{\mu} + p u^{\mu} = -ho\, u^{\mu}.$$
Thus, $u^{\mu}$ is an eigenvector with eigenvalue $-ho$. Since $u^{\mu}$ is timelike by normalization, this eigenvector is timelike and non-degenerate.

Now consider any vector $X^{
u}$ orthogonal to $u^{
u}$, i.e., satisfying $u_{
u} X^{
u} = 0$. Acting with $T^{\mu}{}_{
u}$ on $X^{
u}$ gives
$$T^{\mu}{}_{
u} X^{
u} = (ho + p) u^{\mu} u_{
u} X^{
u} + p \delta^{\mu}{}_{
u} X^{
u} = 0 + p X^{\mu} = p X^{\mu}.$$
Therefore, every vector in the 3-dimensional subspace orthogonal to $u^{\mu}$ is an eigenvector with eigenvalue $p$. These eigenvectors are spacelike in the comoving frame, and the eigenvalue $p$ is triply degenerate.

In the comoving frame with $u^{\mu} = (1,0,0,0)$ and $g_{\mu
u} = \eta_{\mu
u} = \mathrm{diag}(-1,1,1,1)$, one can also compute directly
$$T^{\mu
u} = \mathrm{diag}(ho, p, p, p), \quad T^{\mu}{}_{
u} = T^{\mu\alpha} g_{\alpha
u} = \mathrm{diag}(-ho, p, p, p),$$
confirming the eigenvalues $-ho$ (timelike, non-degenerate) and $p$ (spacelike, triply degenerate).

Hence the correct statement is that the eigenvalues are $-ho$ and $p$, with the $-ho$ eigenvalue associated with the timelike four-velocity and the $p$ eigenvalue triply degenerate in the spacelike subspace.
